<font color="#FF0000">NEWS FROM TODAY'S OREGONIAN  </font><br>
<tt>Tue Jan 27  0:51:14 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
There was a story in the Oregonian today which read, &quot;Forgiveness heals Vietnam pain, vet says.&quot;  The subtitle reads, &quot;Speaking at a forum in Bend, a former U.S. Arum captain stresses the improtance of ending grudges formed during the divisive war.&quot;  <br><br>
This copyrighted story by Gordon Gregory of the Oregonian discusses the High Desert Forum in Bend, Oregon, where former U.S. Army Capt. John Plummer, who is now a United Methodist Church minister, talked about his Vietnam experiences.  &quot;Plummer...met Kim Phuc at the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington after she gave a short speech.  She was 9 when Plummer helped coordinate a napalm strike on her village, Trang Bang...<br><br>
&quot;Pl0ummer said he had been toldthere were no 'friendlies' in the village when he released the jets that provided air support.<br><br>
&quot;Several days later, he saw the photo in the Stars and Stripes newspaper.<br><br>
The article goes on to tell of his problems after the war, and his meeting Phuc 14 months ago.  He stated that he was sorry, and didn't mean to hurt her.  She said to him &quot;I forgive, I forgive,&quot; and according to the story his guilt vanished.  Plummer is 50, and now lives in Purcellvisse, Va.<br><br>
In view of the topic of this thread, I thought others would like to hear of this story.  Lien, I'm not sure that this is the same story that you referred to, but thought you'd like to know about it.  If anyone's interested in it, you can reach the Oregonian by e-mail at:  oped@news.oregonian.com
